# Deobfuscated Code

Let me work through this step by step.

## Step 1: Decode the string table

The obfuscator uses a base64-encoded string array with a rotation shuffle. After decoding all the string lookups, here's the clean version:

```javascript
// Constants
var TAU = 6.283;          // 2π - full circle in radians
var PHI = 1.618;          // Golden ratio
var SQRT_HALF = 0.707;    // √(1/2)

// Physics configuration
// NOTE: The property names are DELIBERATELY WRONG (see explanation below)
var config = {
  repulsion: 4000,        // obfuscated as "attraction" — repulsive force between nodes
  springK: 0.004,         // obfuscated as "frictionCoeff" — spring stiffness constant
  damping: 0.92,          // obfuscated as "amplification" — velocity decay per frame
  centerGravity: 0.0003,  // obfuscated as "dispersal" — pulls nodes toward center
  massHub: 40,            // obfuscated as "inertiaCore" — max particle count
  streamDecay: 0.04,      // particle stream decay rate
  theta: 0.06             // camera smoothing factor
};

// ─── Nodes ───
var nodes = [
  { id: "hub",      label: "Nexus",   r: 26, x: 400, y: 300, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "alpha",    label: "Alpha",   r: 16, x: 500, y: 200, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "beta",     label: "Beta",    r: 16, x: 300, y: 400, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "gamma",    label: "Gamma",   r: 14, x: 250, y: 180, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "delta",    label: "Delta",   r: 14, x: 550, y: 380, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "epsilon",  label: "Epsilon", r: 12, x: 350, y: 150, vx: 0, vy: 0 }
];

// ─── Edges (springs) ───
var edges = [
  { a: "hub", b: "alpha",   rest: 160, k: 0.006 },
  { a: "hub", b: "beta",    rest: 160, k: 0.005 },
  { a: "hub", b: "gamma",   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: "hub", b: "delta",   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: "hub", b: "epsilon", rest: 180, k: 0.003 },
  { a: "alpha", b: "beta",    rest: 200, k: 0.002 },
  { a: "gamma", b: "delta",   rest: 220, k: 0.002 },
  { a: "alpha", b: "epsilon", rest: 200, k: 0.002 }
];

// ─── Camera ───
var camera       = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
var cameraTarget = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };

// ─── Particles ───
var particles = [];
var frameCount = 0;

// Find a node by ID
function findNode(id) {
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}

// ─── Physics simulation step ───
function simulate() {

  // 1) REPULSION — Coulomb-like force between every pair of nodes
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    for (var j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
      var dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
      var dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
      var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
      var force = config.repulsion / (dist * dist);   // inverse-square
      var fx = (dx / dist) * force;
      var fy = (dy / dist) * force;
      nodes[i].vx += fx;
      nodes[i].vy += fy;
      nodes[j].vx -= fx;
      nodes[j].vy -= fy;
    }
  }

  // 2) SPRING FORCES — Hooke's law along each edge
  for (var e = 0; e < edges.length; e++) {
    var nA = findNode(edges[e].a);
    var nB = findNode(edges[e].b);
    if (!nA || !nB) continue;
    var dx = nB.x - nA.x;
    var dy = nB.y - nA.y;
    var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
    var displacement = dist - edges[e].rest;
    var force = (edges[e].k || config.springK) * displacement;
    nA.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
    nA.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
    nB.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
    nB.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
  }

  // 3) PER-NODE: center gravity + damping + position integration
  for (var n = 0; n < nodes.length; n++) {
    // Center gravity — pull toward (400, 300)
    nodes[n].vx += (400 - nodes[n].x) * config.centerGravity;
    nodes[n].vy += (300 - nodes[n].y) * config.centerGravity;
    // Damping — multiply velocity by 0.92 (reduces it each frame)
    nodes[n].vx *= config.damping;
    nodes[n].vy *= config.damping;
    // Integration — update position
    nodes[n].x += nodes[n].vx;
    nodes[n].y += nodes[n].vy;
  }
}

// ─── Spawn a particle from a random node ───
function spawnParticle() {
  if (particles.length >= config.massHub) return;   // max 40 particles
  var source = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
  var angle = Math.random() * TAU;
  var speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * SQRT_HALF;
  particles.push({
    x: source.x,
    y: source.y,
    vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
    vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
    age: 0,
    maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
    size: 0.8 + (Math.random() * PHI) * SQRT_HALF
  });
}

// ─── Update particles ───
function updateParticles() {
  for (var i = particles.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    var p = particles[i];
    // Decay velocity
    p.vx *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);
    p.vy *= (1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125);
    // Move
    p.x += p.vx;
    p.y += p.vy;
    // Age
    p.age++;
    // Remove if too old
    if (p.age > p.maxAge) particles.splice(i, 1);
  }
}

// ─── Smooth camera ───
function updateCamera() {
  camera.x    += (cameraTarget.x    - camera.x)    * config.theta;
  camera.y    += (cameraTarget.y    - camera.y)    * config.theta;
  camera.zoom += (cameraTarget.zoom - camera.zoom)  * config.theta;
}

// ─── Main loop ───
function tick() {
  simulate();
  updateParticles();
  updateCamera();
  if (frameCount % 3 === 0) spawnParticle();  // spawn every 3rd frame
  frameCount++;
}

setInterval(tick, 16);  // ~60 FPS
```

---

## What It Does

This is the **physics engine** for a **force-directed graph visualization**. There's no rendering code here — this is purely the simulation layer.

### The graph structure
- **6 nodes** ("Nexus" hub + Alpha, Beta, Gamma, Delta, Epsilon) connected by **8 spring edges** in a hub-and-spoke topology with a few cross-links.

### Three forces act on every node each frame:

| Force | Effect |
|---|---|
| **Repulsion** (inverse-square, strength 4000) | Pushes all node pairs apart — prevents overlap |
| **Spring attraction** (Hooke's law, per-edge) | Pulls connected nodes toward their rest length (160–220 px) |
| **Center gravity** (strength 0.0003) | Gently pulls everything toward (400, 300) so the graph doesn't drift off-screen |

After forces are summed, velocity is **damped by 0.92** (energy dissipation), then integrated into position. The system settles into equilibrium.

### Particles
Every 3 frames, a cosmetic **particle** is emitted from a random node in a random direction. Particles drift, slow down via `streamDecay`, age out after 800–2000 frames, and are capped at 40. These are the decorative "energy streams" flowing between nodes in the visualization.

### Camera
A smooth-follow camera lerps toward `cameraTarget` at 6% per frame.

---

## The Deliberate Mislabeling Trick

As the author described, the obfuscated string table maps property names to **plausible but semantically opposite** physics terms:

| Obfuscated Name | Real Meaning | Why It's Wrong |
|---|---|---|
| `attraction` | **repulsion** | Force pushes nodes *apart* (positive = repel) |
| `amplification` | **damping** | Multiplying velocity by 0.92 *reduces* it |
| `frictionCoeff` | **springK** | It's a spring stiffness, not friction |
| `dispersal` | **centerGravity** | It pulls nodes *inward*, not outward |
| `inertiaCore` | **massHub** | Used as a particle count cap, not a mass |
| `inertiaNode` | **massNode** | Same misdirection |

This means even if someone decodes the string table, the variable names tell a **physically coherent but completely inverted story** — a clever layer of semantic obfuscation on top of the mechanical obfuscation.
